posts.title: Westworld Season 1, Episode 7: Fruition
posts.text:
Privacy Policy Theres no reason to take Ford at his word. It seems unlikely that simply telling stories is his endgame any more than it is for Delos, because these machines are too sophisticated to serve merely as high-end Chuck E. Cheese automatons for libidinous rich guys. Lee Sizemore, the fatuous narrative director, seems like the only person still arguing for that version of Westworld, and hes several notches down on the corporate hierarchy. All we know is that Ford and the corporate brass at Delos have opposing visions for the park, but what those visions are remains to be seen. At a minimum, the park doesnt appear to be a means to end for Ford like it is for Delos, which has kept it under the microscope like a 35-year-old petri dish. An old-fashioned Western shoot-em-up in hostile territory may have gobbled up most of the episodes budget, but the true centerpiece had Charlotte and Theresa staging a violent scene between two hosts. The fight was ostensibly enacted to expose the parks poor maintainence of its hosts behavioral safeguards and the danger that poses for guests. But Ford and Benard soon see the demonstration for what it is: a pretext for firing Bernard and for nudging Ford toward retirement. They take it as a clarifying moment, like the opening salvo in a war for control over Westworld. 
Advertisement Continue reading the main story Anthony Hopkins has been playing Fords true feelings close to the vest, delivering monologues with the imperious arrogance of a man whose genius is most keenly understood by himself. But in that final moment with Theresa, when Ford orders her murder with the line, Perhaps you can help her, Bernard, Hopkins summons the blithe indifference of his Hannibal Lecter. Westworld turns him into a righteous sociopath, every bit the monster Theresa accuses him of being, but in defense of an artistic vision under attack by his corporate masters. In another life, he could be a Hollywood film director. Paranoid Androids  Bernards affection for Lewis Carroll is a prime example of the shows weakness for interpreting itself. The blurred line between the authentic and the phony in Westworld doesnt need any additional clarification from Alice in Wonderland.  After a week off, we rejoin Dolores and William as they continue their trek into the great unknown, passing through Smoochtown along the way. Its hard not to hear what Williams escort said to him when he asked if she was real or not: If you cant tell, does it matter? It mattered to William on his first days in the park, when he was trying to be the white hat and resisting the temptations around him. But Dolores has him bewitched. Ive been pretending my whole life, he tells her. Then I come here and I get a glimpse of a life in which I dont have to pretend, a life in which I can be truly alive. The irony of those words land hard, because hes fooled himself into believing that a pretend relationship is a real one. Dolores seems capable of breaking more than his heart.  The slight slowdown of the player-piano music as Maeve begins her morning is a nice touch. She knows the routine and the script, and shes hearing the notes so clearly that she annoyed enough to shut them down. She could have lashed out at the techs who pick up Clementine, but shes smart enough to wait in the grass a while longer.  Thandie Newton looks to be having the time of her life as Maeve gains confidence and a certain malevolent sheen. Maeves power over men existed before her self-awareness, but now that shes given herself an upgrade, shes smarter and less inhibited than her handlers. And she can die a million times, too.

posts.text:
Follow Us  2016 Bustle Charlotte Makes A Move Against Ford On Westworld, But The Parks Architect Is A Dangerous Foe By Jefferson Grubbs an hour ago 
Last week, we finally had the pleasure of meeting Charlotte Hale on Westworld , the enigmatic character played by Creed actress (and future Thor: Ragnarok star) Tessa Thompson. At first glance, she appeared to be an excitable guest at the park, decompressing at Westworld's luxurious resort before returning to the real world. Then she was revealed to actually be the representative mentioned earlier by Dr. Ford, the Executive Director of the Delos board sent to investigate the various goings-on at the park. This week, Charlotte proved herself to be a worthy foe when she made a bold move against Ford himself. 
In the eyes of the Delos Corporation, Ford is officially now more trouble than he's worth. He's undertaking a massive new narrative that is sucking up resources and causing disruptions in other ongoing storylines. He's hoarding the company's intellectual property, refusing to let it be backed up on any outside servers for emergency purposes. And let's not forget he's responsible for the recent host glitches thanks to his experiment in "reveries." (Bernard may have publicly taken responsibility for that one, but Charlotte saw right through that charade.) 
Charlotte needed a way to prove that the problems caused by Ford's reveries were making the hosts dangerous in order to get him removed from his position. So she abducted Clementine from the Mariposa and had her brought belowdecks, where the sympathetic sex worker became a pawn in the corporate maneuvers. Charlotte put on a show for Ford, Bernard, and Theresa in which she had an employee punch Clementine in the face; and when she ordered Clementine to reset and wake again, the host appeared to remember the assault and viciously attacked her attacker. 
There were two twists to this scenario, one public and one private. The public twist was that the "employee" was actually just another host, although Clementine wasn't programmed to know that. However, the private twist was that the entire scenario was manufactured by Charlotte and her own team of programmers. Clementine didn't actually attack anyone of her own free will, and it certainly wasn't caused by the reveries. It was all just a ploy to get Bernard to admit that Ford was the one who coded the reveries. 
However, Charlotte's plan backfired when Bernard refused to betray Ford  so she just fired Bernard instead. (Another twist later in the episode made Bernard's intense loyalty to Ford even more understandable.) Charlotte may not have won this battle against Ford but she's determined to win the war.

posts.text:
Ford might launch it in India since a lot of manufacturers already offer cross-hatches in the country

Ford has revealed the cross version of the Figo , the Ka Trail, at the ongoing 2016 Sao Paulo International Motor Show in Brazil. For the uninitiated, the second-generation Figo is known as 'Ka' in the Brazilian market and 'Ka+' in Europe . Like all the cross-hatches, the Ka Trail is essentially a rugged looking version of the stock hatch. It will go on sale early next year in Brazil. Though there is no official word from the American automaker, Ford might introduce this version in India since a lot of manufacturers already offer cross hatches in the country.

Speaking of the changes, Ford has offered the customary wheel arch cladding in the Trail version and it rides higher off the ground compared to the regular Figo. The front and rear bumpers get faux silver skid plates, while the vehicle gets side mirrors, door handles and 15-inch alloy wheels with grey highlights. Also, it comes with orange and grey vinyl decals on the sides and at the rear. On the inside, the Trail version comes with fabric plus leather upholstery with contrasting stitching in orange and green along with sporty pedals and door sill plates with a Trail logo.

If Ford plans to launch the Figo Trail in the country, it will remain unaltered mechanically and will carry forward the current set of powertrains as it has in the Brazilian market.

posts.text:

Photo by David Carson, Ford, SLU look to rebound after season-opening loss (  ) David Carson 
Saint Louis University Billikens head coach Travis Ford (center) reacts as Ball State builds their lead in the first half during a game between the Ball State Cardinals and Saint Louis University Billikens at the Chaifetz Arena in St. Louis on Friday, Nov. 11, 2016. Photo by David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com David Carson 
Ball State Cardinals forward Franko House (15) defends Saint Louis Billikens guard Zeke Moore (23) during a game between the Ball State Cardinals and Saint Louis University Billikens at the Chaifetz Arena in St. Louis on Friday, Nov. 11, 2016. Photo by David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com 
When reality hit coach Travis Ford in the first half of his regular-season debut at St. Louis University, the frustration was evident in a way that rarely was recognizable on the face of his predecessor. 
The Billikens were slammed in the opening minutes and never recovered. And Ford showed the crowd of 7,165 exactly how he felt. He yelled, he confronted, he put his face into his hands and rubbed his forehead. 
As a player I loved challenges, he said. I was wanting to get in that game. 
SLU had many problems in an 85-64 loss to Ball State, and Ford had many ideas but little time to implement change as SLU faces a quick turnaround to play Southern Utah on Monday night at Chaifetz Arena. 
His postgame message ultimately came down to wanting his players to set a higher standard, whether they get there or not. 
They all have to be willing to get out of their comfort zones and take a chance to say Im going to be this good, Ford said. When you set that high standard, you have to figure out how youre going to get there. I told them its absolutely worth it when you do it. 
Im not big on accepting mediocrity. I told them I made more mistakes than anybody out there. But my personality is to try to figure it out. I told them when they come back (Saturday) morning all the coaches will have the same clothes on. Were not going anywhere tonight. Well figure it out. 
Ford and his coaches ended up meeting until early Saturday morning. 
Ford is hoping that the team he saw in the second half is closer to what he will see on a regular basis. The Billikens scored 19 points in the first half, had 11 turnovers and had trouble generating good shots. 
They scored 45 in the second half, pushed the tempo more, had five turnovers and shot 44 percent. 
We broke down our offense like never before in the first half, Ford said. I told them in a timeout, You look like a different team. Youre abandoning the offense. We didnt even get to option one hardly and definitely didnt get to option two or three. Thats what happens when you try to make it all up real quick. 
The opening loss provided the first look at how Ford might divvy up playing time. He started redshirt freshman Elliott Welmer and gave only eight minutes to centers Austin Gillmann and Matt Neufeld. Every starter played at least 25 minutes, which is a bit different from the last two years, when more players were used and for shorter minutes. 
Returning players Davell Roby and Reggie Agbeko had the best production and both sang the praises of Fords system after the game. 
The system is great, Roby said. I think we got pretty good looks but didnt put them in. I know we shot horrific from the free-throw line. The good thing about college basketball is we get another game Monday. 
Stu Durando
